<p>Check out this simple html.</p>  <pre><code>&lt;html xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"&gt;     &lt;head&gt;         &lt;meta http-equiv="X-UA-Compatible" content="IE=7" /&gt;          &lt;title&gt;&lt;/title&gt;         &lt;style&gt;             .box {                 cursor: pointer;             }              .box:hover {                 background-color: yellow;             }         &lt;/style&gt;         &lt;script src="http://ajax.aspnetcdn.com/ajax/jquery/jquery-1.11.1.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;         &lt;script&gt;             $(function () {                 function updateText() {                     $(this).text('newnewnewnewnewnewnewnewnewnewnew');                 }                  function updateBox() {                     $(this).replaceWith($('&lt;span class="box"&gt;newnewnewnewnewnewnewnewnewnewnew&lt;/span&gt;'));                 }                  $('.box').click(updateBox);             })         &lt;/script&gt;     &lt;/head&gt; &lt;body&gt;     &lt;span class="box"&gt;oldoldoldoldoldoldoldoldoldoldoldoldoldold. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="box"&gt;oldoldoldoldoldoldoldoldoldoldoldoldoldold. &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/body&gt; &lt;/html&gt; </code></pre>  <p>The bug exits in IE7. As mouse hovering on the text, the background color becomes yellow. <strong>But after you click on the text, the hover effect is MISSING in IE7.</strong> Only if you slightly move your mouse can the hover effect be back.  </p>  <p>It would be opposite if you use <code>updateText</code> instead of <code>updateBox</code> -- the hover effect is still visible even the mouse is no longer hovering on the text after click.</p>  <p>Expected effect is the case in Chrome/IE11.</p>  <p>Any idea? Can I force re-exam which element is being hovered after <code>updateText</code> or <code>updateBox</code>?</p>